The paper discusses the use of random samples to approximate properties of geometric configurations, which is a topic that falls under computational geometry (cs.CG). The concepts of $\epsilon$-approximations and $\epsilon$-nets are also related to data structures (cs.DS) and discrete mathematics (cs.DM). Additionally, the paper may be relevant to the sub-categories of computational complexity (cs.CC) and numerical analysis (cs.NA) due to the quantitative properties being considered.
